ntury. According to Branson, episodes in both women's lives illustrate their struggles within a society that constrained women's activities and ambitions. She argues that both women simultaneously tried to conform to and manipulate the dominant sexual, economic, and social ideologies of the time. In their own lives and through their writing, the pair challenged conventions prescribed by these ideologies to further their own ends and redefine what was possible for women in early American public life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFemale offenderszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiavBiography. 0aSex rolezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen authors, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 0aWomenzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiavBiography. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220142040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201420423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812201420/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041349-6  Penn Press eBook Package American History  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  